                     <handDesc>

                        <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic" corresp="#p1_i1 #p2_i1.1 #p2_i1.2 #p2_i1.3 #p2_i1.5 #p2_i1.6 #p2_i1.7" >
                           <seg type="script">Second half of the 19th-century script, probably closer to the middle.</seg>
                            <seg type="ink">Black (brownish); red.</seg>
                           <seg type="rubrication">A lot of rubricated words, in the main hand;
                              rubrication is executed in the main hand, probably after the copying
                              of the main text (in some cases one can see that the space left for
                              rubricated word was not enough). </seg>
                                <desc>Somewhat hasty and irregular; by a mediocre scribe.
                                Slightly right-sloping script, downstrokes mostly parallel, the tops of the letters slightly inclined to the left.
                                Slender, rounded letter shapes show some tendency to cursive.
                                ጵ has the standard modern shape (<locus target="#9va"/>), the top of ጥ is nearly plain in some cases only (cp. <locus target="#10rb"/> against
                                 <locus target="#36rb #49rb"/>),
                                 the 6th order-marker of ግ is emphasized, set up on the extended line, the left leg of ለ is leant upon
                                  the right leg.
                                 </desc>
                                    </handNote>
                     </handDesc>

                     <decoDesc>

                        <decoNote type="drawing" xml:id="d1">
                           <locus target="#4v" facs="005"/>fine bicolour miniature (black and red),
                           St George of Lydda</decoNote>
                        <decoNote type="drawing" xml:id="d2">
                           <locus target="#5r" facs="005"/>fine bicolour miniature (black and red),
                           St Mary with Child</decoNote>
                        <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d3">Ornamental bands.</decoNote>
                        <decoNote xml:id="d4">Ff. 3-6 containing the miniatures, unruled (only a
                           frame on the leaves with miniatures), of smaller or irregular size. In
                           fact it is not 100% sure that the miniatures were prepared and infixed
                           into the text block later, separately. The miniatures were painted by a
                           professional artist; I see a tacket in the fold above, between f. 4v and
                           f. 5r. Another explanation cannot be excluded: the quire with miniatures
                           was bound together with regular quires, and the tacket was left by
                           chance. There is a little bit of speculation, and it is a matter of
                           interpretation (to understand better, one would need to have the books in
                           the hands) but from the point of view of systematics it is better to
                           register the leaves with miniature as a separate codicological/production
                           unit. There is a number of books where miniatures (written on unruled
                           leaves) similarly build a separate unit, the result of a separate
                           production process.</decoNote>
                     </decoDesc>

